I took 2 videos of Josepha yesterday in our pilates session and I thought this was a great image for you to see why focusing on your core even during standing arm stretches is important.

Do you notice the difference?

As a teacher my eyes👀are always on you ( it’s for your benefit😘). 

Many people might look at this image and ask “what is she showing? Or that exercise doesn’t look hard. It’s not about making things hard. 

What I am trying to show you here is the difference when you do an exercise without support, guidance or feedback vs when you have a teacher who cares about you and wants the best for you ( that’s me😘). 

Josepha has had many surgeries for #breastcancer & #ovariancancer. She also had radiation to her pelvis and breasts. I understand the long term side effects of radiation to the abdomen and pelvis myself. 

The 2nd picture on the right you can see Josepha isn’t using her core to lift her arms. Look at her hips push forward, her back away and her arms go higher over her head. Bigger doesn’t mean better.

After curing her to focus on her core 360 ( and more) her posture totally changed. She also said her back felt better🙌🏻The win🙌🏻🙌🏻🙌🏻🙌🏻🙌🏻

If you need help understanding why your back hurts after surgery I can help you. You could have had surgery 56 years ago like Josepha and still benefit from learning correct core technique. It’s NEVER too late.

What is your story?

You may think my story is about me surviving #ovariancancer, but the truth is that I named my Instagram handle #cancersavedmylife because there was a much bigger story there to heal besides cancer. 

We all have a story. Even if you don’t think you do. I want you to imagine you have two sides. A light side & a dark side. The light side is all the positive qualities within yourself. The dark side is just the opposite. It’s that voice that tells you that you are not enough, you don’t matter, you are not worth it. That voice can get very dark.

I know that voice very well. In my past I was ashamed of that voice because I was told it was BAD to feel sad. It was BAD to complain about your feelings & when you did people would think less of you😭 So I held my sadness in for many years.

“Nobody cares about your story Emilee” are words I will NEVER get out of my head. When somebody tells you nobody cares about your story that is very hurtful. It’s even more hurtful when it’s your intimate partner. 

I am grateful today that I have found a partner who loves all my qualities, both the light and the dark. 

Today I can have compassion for people who have hurt me in the past because I’ve learned that we ALL have a story to heal. Cancer was just my catalyst to get a jumpstart and I am grateful for that because I really could not go on living anymore believing all those negative voices in my head telling me that nobody cares about me. I’ve been to the dark side. I crawled my way back to reinventing the story that I want to create. 

I’ve learned that I was very codependent. When you try to please your partner out of fear of rejection or abandonment, it never works. The most important person you need to love and heal is the story with yourself. 

I’ll ask again. What is the story you need to heal?

On the other side of the emotional pain you may be burying is joy, peace and a life you deserve. 

Trust me. Life doesn’t happen to you, it’s happening for you. Create the life you want. You do have a choice.

The story you are telling yourself really is just a myth. Of course I matter. Of course my dad loved me. He was 35, a Vietnam Vet, he has a story too❤️

I had an AHA moment this morning.

I’ve never had a book signing or really promoted my book.

Why?

I’ve uncovered through my coaching sessions that I had disowned a quality called confidence. You might see me on the cover of my own book looking confident, happy and smiling, but I wasn’t. 

Let me explain.

I am 100% confident in what I teach, especially to women who are recovering from cancer. What I wasn’t ( past tense) confident in was the belief that I could make a difference in peoples lives. 

I doubted myself and my teaching skills because what I teach isn’t what others teach. It makes me different and I never liked being different. As a young child who had cancer and who was bald I wanted to fit in and be like everyone else.

So it hit me today that I have been hiding my own gift which is teaching.

I’ve been making myself invisible and what I say I really want to do is help people heal and thrive after cancer.

I have a hard time promoting myself because it feels like I’m showing off or bragging. That is another quality I’ve disowned.

But what I’ve learned is that these disowned qualities that we are triggered by in others are qualities that we all have within us. We just need to RECLAIM them. 

I am recusing confidence in who I am and what I do.

What are you reclaiming?

Need help uncovering your disowned qualities? Sign up today to take a LIVE workshop with me Jan 10th and I’ll help you see that the light you have disowned is inside of you waiting to shine bright❤️

My FREE workshop is for #cancersurvivors and you can sign up⬆️in bio under Reinvent Your Life After Cancer link and I’ll send more details soon❤️

Santa asked me what I wanted?

I whispered in his ear, “MORE time”.

I wanted more time to watch my kids grow up. I wanted more time for a cure for cancer to come. I wanted more time to show my kids that their mom loved them them so much! I wanted more time to see how the rest of my story was going to unfold. I wasn’t ready for my story to be over😭

Most people, including my doctors thought that was my last Christmas. I was told my advanced stage of ovarian cancer was incurable. That was 2015. The worst year of my life.
Cancer + a divorce. My first Christmas alone I wanted it to be very special for my kids. Honestly, the only thing I wanted more than anything was for my kids to love me for who I was. I tried my hardest to bake my Aunts monkey bread but it turned into a disaster. The oven caught on fire and the fire trucks showed up. The kids got in my car and hid I totally embarrassed the kids and they were all yelling, “ this is the worst Christmas ever”. Even worst they said they wanted to go to dads. I failed Christmas. I can laugh today, but honestly I thought I was the worst mom ever.  I didn’t know how I was going to survive cancer and I surely didn’t know how I was going to survive being a single mom. I did and today I share my story to give you hope.

I do #believe in #miracles❤️

This Christmas 7 years later my life has completely transformed. 

❤️ I am healthy

🙏I am cancer free 

❤️I know my worth 

❤️I am loved 

❤️ I have healed my story 

Today I know I am a good mom😘

I no longer bake mondybread😂

And i am so excited to see my NEW kitchen that we have been building for the past 2 years. I can’t wait to cook for my family and a bunch of teenagers😂

Christmas is my favorite day of the year because it brings back so many memories ( not all good) but I see how far I’ve grown and healed my life.

Thank you Santa! I am forever grateful❤️for more time on earth 

I have compassion for myself today because mom isn’t perfect and mom is always learning. Sending all you newly single moms an extra special Merry Christmas because I know how hard that first Christmas on your own can be.
You are doing a great job and don’t ever forget that❤️

My heart is happy and sad all at the same time❤️😭

2018 I gave Alvin his 1st Christmas since he was a child. People asked me all the time, why do you care so much about Alvin?

Alvin is a human.

He is a young man, trapped in a little boys body who has had a very traumatic childhood. 

I care about Alvin because nobody else does💔

It breaks my heart to watch people suffer.

The #1 thing my own story has taught me is that everybody needs more compassion for themselves and for others.

How could I just sit there and watch this young man starve on the streets and watch him freeze outside with only socks on his feet somedays?

I couldn’t.

If I was rich I would help more people like Alvin. I am a very empathic person and sometimes is wears me down because I get so caught up feeling so much sadness for them.

Alvin had a mom once.

Alvin asked me why I talk to him and thanked me and told me that nobody has ever believed in him or loved him.
That literally crushed my heart. I met Alvin when I was going through cancer & a divorce. I was in a lot of emotional pain and Alvin was always sitting by my studio door and smiled at me. We became friends. I wanted to know more about him, but he was very cautious as he doesn’t trust most people.

I haven’t seen Alvin in a year and wasn’t able to give him his yearly Christmas in my little studio. This made me very sad.
I worry if Alvin is even alive?

There is a guy who walks the streets in #santabarbara who looks just like him, but it’s not him.

If you see him please let me know so I can find him.

My heart is happiest when I’m helping people.

When is your heart happiest?

I woke up to this view from my bedroom.

PEACE was my word for 2022. In order to feel more peace, I had to create it.

This journey of finding peace for me started 9 years ago. I was asked by my therapist what two words do you want more of in your life. She asked me to write them down.

I wrote peace & respect.

There is a lot to these words and I’ll write more later, but right now I am reflecting on these words.

I wanted more peace in my life. My body does not respond well to chaos, screaming, yelling. My body was desperate for something to change.

By the time I figured this out, it was too late. I was diagnosed with cancer, an incurable cancer I read,ovarian cancer is brutal😭

I was desperate for a cure, so I searched outside of the box. I hired an energy healer, a shaman, a Chinese dr, a life coach and an end of life therapist. It was during one of my end of life therapy sessions that I had my AHA moment. I am not ready to die. I have more life to live.

Although at the time it seemed impossible, I would go to my moms house in Mt. Shasta to look for healing. I had no idea what I was looking for, except I heard this place was magical and healing. It’s something you have to believe, and so I did.

I would go out on the lake and practice my #yoga and talk to the mountain. I would ask her to please save me and tell her I was sorry for everything I ever did in my life. I talked to her like she was my only friend and she guided me. I know it sounds crazy, but it was my journey.

Every time I come here I feel so calm and peaceful. We ended up buying a house to remodel during the pandemic and we chose this house because of this view.

It’s very spiritual place here and before my cancer I was not a spiritual person. What I’ve learned this year is that spirituality can be whatever you want it to be. I’ve found myself and therefore I’m more at peace. This is my spirituality.

My spirit lives in these mountains and around the lake and the forest.
I feel most at peace here.

2022 has been one of the best years of my life. I’m looking forward to making 2023 YOUR best year of your life. 

I’ll ask you the same question I was asked:
What 2 words do you want more in 2023?

Every year for the past 7 years I have been on a path of spiritual growth, self improvement and transformation. 

The #1 thing that has worked best for me to transform my life is #lifecoaching, but not just any coaching. I have been part of a professional community for the past 7 years with other professionals who push and challenge my growth.

Every year I commit to taking 1-2 NEW coach trainings so that I help always bring more value to you😘

When you invest in yourself it impacts everyone around you.

It’s a win:win for all.

I used to think a relationship was about finding someone else who was going to save me and make my life better, but what I’ve learned and want to help you learn is that the #1 relationship is with yourself.

Relationships are meant to help us grow. No relationship is going to save you but the one with yourself!

Imagine what could be possible for you when you started to believe that you were worth it🤷‍♀️

I want to help you grow in 2023 and become the best version of yourself!

DM me and let’s set up a time to talk about the relationship you want to improve this year (hint: it will always start with you first).

P.s. 7 years ago I never imagined I would be a life coach and here I am all because cancer saved my life. I can now share the wisdom I’ve learned from my mentors

Yesterday at the gym ( my place of work) Shawn asked me if I could teach him some barre exercises to help strengthen his hips. It’s been awhile since I taught #bootybarre but I said YES!

I forgot how much fun it is.

To be honest, it’s been 7 years since I’ve taught because my body was struggling pre and post cancer. Not to mention I had hip surgery for a torn labrum and FAI surgery on my right hip. My barre days were done😭

Yesterday gave me #hope again. I had given up on #barre 

I had so much fun teaching Shawn who is a professional football player that I totally forgot about my hips.

I am watching this video back and I’m thinking to myself, “ hey, my form isn’t so bad😂”. The story I’ve been telling myself is that my body is broken. 

I just proved that story wrong!!

It may not feel it work the same, but it can still do hard things.

Sometimes you just need to get out there again and give it a try.

What do you want to get back out there and try?

Thank you @shawn_poindexter1 for coming to ask me to teach you some exercises yesterday because you showed me that I can still do hard things🙏🙏🙏🙏🙏🙏🙏🙏🙏🙏🙏🙏🙏

P.S. What story are you ready to give up in order to prove yourself wrong!!!

P.S.S. If you love barre and want the best teacher ever follow my bestie @traceymallett @bootybarre I only teach barre privately 😂

I’m thinking ( maybe ) of starting a podcast🤷‍♀️ It’s something I’ve been wanting to do, but the ONLY thing that is holding me back is that I don’t know how to start.

I’ve been sharing parts of my story here for 7 years now. There is SO much more to my story that I want to share that I can’t express in limited text. 

I want my podcast to help other cancer survivors like me SEE what is possible when you take action and heal the deeper part of you that chemotherapy doesn’t heal. I know some of you know what I mean.

I’m been blessed to work with some amazing professionals and feel called to pay it forward. 
Part of the hero’s journey that I have been following for 7 years is that when you cross over ( imagine a bridge and you are stuck. You can’t cross, but you want to but something is holding you back) you pay it forward. You pass on the lessons that have helped you. 

I am fully ready to share and help you cross that bridge❤️

When you do, you will never look back with regret, anger, sadness or grief. You will have learned to have so much self-compassion for yourself and forgiven yourself and others ( which had been the #1 step in my healing journey). 

In 2013, Oct 7-12 I attended a life changing retreat. That was pre cancer. I had NO idea that if I didn’t change my behavior and my life that I would get cancer again. 
I went home, but didn’t finish the work. Attending a 4 or 5 day retreat, is great, but unless you continue to do the work, you may find yourself falling back into old patterns which could be causing chaos and unhappiness in your life. 

I’m going to share my horse story at the retreat that was LIFE changing for me. I have to rush to the studio now to teach, but I want you to know there is more I do than just teaching Pilates & yoga.

I want to help you move forward and never look back with regret.

P.s. I had to look back at the camera and my new life now because some days it’s hard to believe that I DID it. I put my past behind me and truly healed my inner child who was so hurt❤️

Last night I was at dinner and out of no where my abdomen froze up and felt like it was being twisted and stabbed with a knife. I tried to focus and enjoy talking to a friend who I haven’t seen, but my mind could not focus. 

Those of you who really know me, know that I LOVE food and I love going out to dinner so when Emilee doesn’t order any food, there is a problem😂

For a moment I started to experience PTSD of the FEELING of the first time I had a bowel obstruction after my ileostomy surgery. It’s VERY common for ANYONE who has had abdominal surgery, colon surgery to experience this because adhesions form inside. First thought was oh F……k NOT this again. FEAR and panic set in, but I did not show it to anyone at the table. I just left and went home ( I could barely walk to my car), but I didn’t want to bother anyone ( one of my old stories, I don’t want to be annoying or needy). 

When I got home, I immediately got in my bed like in this video I made 7 years ago because I had this same horrible pain in the hospital, GAS pain. I gave myself 30 minutes to wait and if the pain didn’t stop I’d go to the ER. You will never imagine the combination of what cured my pain last night. It was almost instant. This pose, Childs pose and I put a pillow under my belly + my husband handed me a Diet Coke to drink. I’m not sure where that came from because we don’t but soda, but it was in our house and saved me. It could be any carbonated drink, but that’s all we had and within a minute I let out the deepest belly burp and OMG the pain stopped.

Trapped gas pain can feel like a bowel obstruction. I am so grateful today I woke up feeling 100% better and that I didn’t have to go to the ER.

Have you ever experienced that kind of pain post abdominal or ileostomy surgery or ileostomy reversal surgery?

What helps you when you have horrible gas pain? Please share because it helps others!!!

There is so much story behind these pictures.

 #1 Cancer doesn’t just affect you, it affects your family ( especially, kids).

#2 I had so much MOM guilt at this stage in my life. I felt like I failed my kids 

#3 You can DECIDE how you want your story to go. That means you can re-write your story EVEN if you felt like me ( hopeless) and uncertain of your future. The story isn’t over yet, so why give up?

In this first picture I want to address CORE feelings. We all have them. My poor kids had to go through a #divorce & #cancer at the same time. Their emotions were 🔥Zoom in on one of the drawings the kids did ( they were not happy to share their feelings, but I thinks it’s good to talk to your kids and be honest so they know that these feelings are normal to feel.

✅Anger
✅Sad
✅Guilty
✅Fear
✅Nervous
✅Jealous
✅Happy

I had a lot of these feelings myself ( minus the happy). I made my kids pose for pictures and told them to smile because I wanted them to have good memories of me if I didn’t make it. They were so annoyed at me😭🤪🤷‍♀️

I am so grateful I did though because looking back at past pictures makes to appreciate my life more and all of the hardships I have gone through. It really does make you stronger if you choose to appreciate the lessons cancer gifts you.

I know not everyone can get there, but if you can, life is more joyful, peaceful and full of possibilities.

My kids are ALL stronger today because of what they went through in life. They are able to take what life has given them and torn it around to being better humans and making the best of life.
I am so proud of my kids.

To any of you moms out there going through cancer, cancer and a divorce I am sending you double hugs today❤️❤️I know it’s hard, but you can do hard things! You are super mom!!!!!!!!

Please tag a mom you know who is going through cancer and maybe a divorce as well during cancer who needs to hear a good outcome!!!! I am here to help ❤️❤️❤️❤️❤️❤️

My #1 struggle with long term survivorship has been pelvic radiation damage. There are many names for it. I often hear my radiologists say to me,”oh, you have radiated hips”. Then they ask how I’m able to dance and teach Pilates. I guess I’ve just learned how to adapt to my body. It’s all I’ve ever known.

When I met Josepha who also had radiation to her pelvis at age 29 for stage 4 #ovariancancer she was the first person who really understood what it felt like. When you have radiation to your pelvis/ abdomen you are at higher risk for #scoliosis ( we both have that), but we don’t let that stop us from moving and having fun.

Today I was teaching Josepha ( age 86) to get some more #mobility ( movement) in her hips ( as she’s aging, her body is getting VERY stiff). 

Movement does NOT have to be hard. Movement should be fun and you shouldn’t hurt yourself trying to do things that your body no longer can do after a major surgery from #cancer.

Nurture your body with love & kindness.

Just move!

Movement is medicine. 

I use Josepha as my example because I want yo live to be 86 like her.

P.s. she’s very serious when she works out, so I have to remind her to smile sometimes😂

The sooner you can move post surgery/ radiation the better to get the tissues healing and blood flow moving💃❤️

If you need 1:1 help, I can guide you and create a weekly movement routine for you using my specific Cancer Core Recovery®️Method. You are unique, which means you need your body needs a specific plan that is just right for you at whatever stage of recovery you are in.

How many days a week are you lifting weights?

How many days a week are you stretching? 

What are you doing for ❤️health?

Do you have a teacher guiding you or are you trying to figure this out all by yourself?

Just some questions for you🙏

Daily Reminder❤️

You do have the power to protect your peace🙏

Never forget that YOU do have a choice.

It doesn’t always feel that way, but YOU do. You have the choice in the way you respond to people who make you angry. YES, you really do. You can match their energy ( more anger) or you can choose to create the inner world that you know you need to survive another day (inner peace).

 To anyone out there reading this who is going through cancer treatment or cancer treatment and a divorce like I did at the same time my words of wisdom today are FIND PEACE🙏

Being angry at the fact that you have cancer is NOT going to help you heal. Your body needs you. Your mind & soul need you. You need to protect every ounce of positive energy so that you can use that as fuel to keep going when you feel like giving up.

I’ve walked in your shoes.

The story of the two wolves: Native American Parable

I share this story with you because it was shared with me and allowed me to see that we all have a story inside of us that needs to be healed.

The story is about an old Cherokee who is teaching his grandson about life. “A fight is going on inside me,” he said to the boy. “It is a terrible fight and it is between two wolves. One is evil- he is angry, envy, sorrow, regret, greed, arrogance, self-pity, guilt, resentment, inferiority, lies, false pride, superiority, and ego.”

He continued, “The other is good- he is joy, peace, love, hope, serenity, humility, kindness, benevolence, empathy, generosity, truth, compassion, and faith. The same fight is going on inside you- and inside every other person, too.”

The grandson thought about it for a minute and then asked his grandfather, “which wolf will win?”

The old Cherokee simply replied, “The one you feed.”

This story serves as an important reminder that we have the power over our experiences and emotions. It may not feel like it at a time of crisis and this is when you need to dig deep within and remember this story. 

The story that you feed is the story that will always win. 

Which story are you going to feed? 

Which story is no longer serving you? 

Sharing our stories with each other helps us feel less alone in our fears. It also helps us see that others struggle with similar stories. 

Please share your story with me. I want to hear it because your story matters!!

The gift that cancer brought me was more time to work on myself🙏 Honestly, it was my wake up call to look at myself and my life and ask myself this question: If I live, what do I want the rest of my life to look like?

What I wanted seemed out of reach. It didn’t seem possible, so I stayed stuck in my comfort zone ( pre-cancer). I am here to tell you that NOTHING is out of reach.

My life was chaos. I was going through a divorce, cancer treatments, trying to run my pilates studio ( I was the only teacher) and trying to hold myself together learning how to be a new single mom.

I was honestly afraid to spend time in this hyperbaric chamber to treat #radiationcystitis that was awakened after more #chemotherapy and #debulking surgery from #ovariancancer. The #1 thing I was fearful of was catching on fire in there. They told me that was possible so I had to shower before I went into the chamber to make sure I had no oils etc on me. Of course I allowed that fear to accelerate in my head. I always went to the worst case scenario. Then, I was fearful I would have an accident on myself ( which I did many times) because my bladder was cut through. I was too proud and too embarrassed to take the diapers they offered me. I said “NO, I don’t need them”, but I really did. Recently I was thinking of this story as I look back 8 years later and I can now see my old self inside that bubble. She was afraid of losing control. She was afraid to be herself. She didn’t want anyone to think she had problems so she smiled, even when she was in pain. She felt isolated and alone and never told anyone because she believed nobody cared around her. Does that girl in the bubble seem like she would be someone who believed that? I share my story because what you see on the outside isn’t what’s what someone feels on the inside.

I have a purpose in life how. 

I’ve healed my body, but more importantly for me is that I’ve healed my old story by learning to have compassion for myself, and forgiveness for myself. Healing is an inside job that nobody else can do. I can be here to guide you when you are ready to heal that old story you tell yourself.

What if you try shifting your lens?

What I mean by this is, what if you shift the way you look at things? What could you see differently?

Later in life, I was diagnosed with a secondary cancer from radiation. This time, advanced late stage 3c #ovariancancer. This time around after more surgeries and a new #ileostomy, I struggled a lot with itchy, dry, burning skin. I had to be extremely cautious with any product I put on my scars, especially around my new #stoma (that’s the area where your intestines comes out through a hole and into a bag to release your 💩). Everyday I cried in my bathroom because I felt so alone & frustrated with my body.
 
Until…. I met the amazing people over at @larocheposayusa who welcomed me to their family. Honestly, they were one of the best things that ever happened to me. One day, I received a gift at my door. My teenage daughter stole it from me because she loved the products so much😂 I can’t even tell you how special I felt that day that somebody sent me a gift for being a #cancersurvior. But, even better than that was this special lotion they have for radiation burns, safe for #cancerpatients that NOBODY else offers. I could go on and on how amazing I felt from using their products, but more importantly, I am part of their cancer squad and I now get to help pay it forward! There are amazing opportunities that come with being a cancer survivor.

Dear Dad,

I think this is the first Father’s Day in my entire life ( I’m 47 years old now) where I finally understand why you died. For most of my life, until just recently I was really mad at you for committing suicide. I’ve learned in my #grief training that we don’t call it that anymore. We now say “death by suicide”. For some reason learning about this topic in a way that creates a better picture in my mind that you were not a bad person, I was not a bad kid and that you “didn’t love me” enough to stay alive for me has helped me heal my old childhood wounds and story around your death. 

The truth is, I was really sad you were never there for me. I never had a dad and that hurt my heart, actually it 💔 But today I can forgive you because it sets my brain free from all of the stories I have made up in my head and all of the what is’s that never happened. I can see the picture all so clear now. 

It wasn’t my fault that I got #cancer at age 4 and then you decided to take your life. But that’s the story my little brain made up and my entire life’s story has been shaped around your death. It’s time to let that go. Maybe it was just my way of holding onto any memory I had of you. This is it. This is all I ever had. A black and white picture. I have no memories of you and that makes me feel sad. I try to be the best mom to my kids so they never feel the loss that I did. But I forgive you. When I was asked to think that maybe you could have had #ptsd from serving in #vietnam and that “maybe” you came back a different person, it helped me to see that you were most likely fighting with your brain and I now have so much more #compassion for you.  I feel sad for you and all of those who come back changed and suffer with #mentalhealth 

I said goodbye to you and watched you be buried in the ground. I saw you in an open casket at the age of 5 and I just don’t think I was ready to process my grief. In fact, I just learned my sadness had a name and that it’s normal for young children who lose a parent to grieve their entire life. Kids ( I am just a big kid now) jump in and out of grief. Today I just wanted to say Happy Father’s Day. I ❤️you. You are never forgotten💫

I never imagined myself becoming a #griefeducator with #davidkessler through my own journey through #cancer.

I always thought I would only be helping the #cancersurvivor, but it turns out that in the past few years in my #pilatesstudio I am been supporting more #widows than I could have imaged. 

To be honest, this was a hard relationship to navigate through because I was so close to his wife. I had a lot of survivors guilt, and always felt so bad that I was happy and alive, and his wife didn’t make it from #ovariancancer. 

I learned to listen a lot in our #movement sessions. I would literally teach a hip opener and witness the release of #emotions. I couldn’t fix the fact that he lost his wife, but I could help him take care of himself because it’s easy to lose yourself in grief. My client Bruce is one of the reasons I decided to become a grief educator. I help my clients #heal pain & hurt through the physical & emotional body. It is what comes natural to me🙏

I have witnessed the many stages of grief my client has gone through and to see him today laughing, smiling and then to hear him tell me his ❤️has been cracked open ( in a good way) brings me such joy.

As your teacher, I will be by your side every step of the journey. Wherever you are at, I will be by your side. 

Something else I’ve experienced personally and with my clients, grief can show up years later. It can show up in the body as dis-ease, that’s what happened to me when I kept my grief in silence. 

Sometimes we can plan what we think we want to do & life shows us differently. I am following my ❤️and allowing the journey to guide me and take me where I am needed. 

This is just a piece of who I AM, for those of you who only think of me as a cancer survivor. I AM a #cancerthriver giving back to the #cancercommunity. Leave a ❤️if this inspired you😘

I began my career teaching right out of college! I saw the impact #yoga was having on people’s lives!

I myself have had countless surgeries, and found myself  frustrated by other teachers not understanding my body.

After my last cancer diagnosis of stage 3c #ovariancancer and having surgery with a new #stoma and #ostomy I decided I wanted to broaden my niche.

It expanded into #cancerrecovery because I understand this path❤️

Being a professional movement educator, I also know how important the emotional body is and how it impacts our physical health.

I’ve always had a hard time putting a label on who I am and who I serve. I just love helping people feel better by empowering them, emotionally & physically!

It’s always nice when you hear from your clients that they were able to run again, when not that long ago, they could barely walk😭

I don’t normally advertise myself🤷‍♀️ I’ve kept myself invisible and small for 25 years, but today I know who I am and who I serve.

I’m confident on that😘

If you need a 1:1 session or know someone who does, you can trust me to help them🙏

What hasn’t changed is my passion for helping others.

What is something you WANT so bad that you will do anything for?

I can name a few myself, but today my share is about becoming a mom.
My story started off feeling hopeless. 

I would never have children of my own because having my first cancer surgery and radiation/#chemotherapy at the age of 4 took that away from me🥲

My story was set or ghostwritten before I was even aware of it.

Growing up I was the ONLY person out of my friends who didn’t have a menstrual period. They thought I was lucky ( I didn’t see it that was).

I grew up with a lot of #bodyshame because I felt different. My #childhoodcancer is where all of my #selfdoubt & fears came from. I constantly lived in fear that I would get cancer again. Guess what? My biggest fear came true, but this time I was able to CHANGE my story!

Of course this was a process & I want to help YOU heal your story + rewrite a new one too😘

The #1 quality I see in myself today that I didn’t recognize before is that I am a very persistent person! If I say I want something, I will MAKE it happen!

At the age of 23 years old, I was married and the only thing I ever wanted was to feel loved and to be a #mom. I think when something is taken from you, the desire to have it becomes greater. That was my experience🤷‍♀️I know it’s not true for everyone, but it was for me at that time. 

The amount of anxiety I felt over having children was off the charts. I felt like I was useless and a failure that I couldn’t give my husband children. So much #shame in that story. 

The thing was…. My story wasn’t over yet. In fact, it hadn’t even started. I gave up before I even tried because I believed what doctors told me. You will NEVER have your own kids😭

They didn’t mention back than that #surrogacy would be a thing. I think even the doctors were in shock that my little 4 year old body that had 2 years of pelvic/abdominal radiation + surgery were shocked. Not to mention that in college I had a partial #hysterectomy which really made my chances seem impossible.

Here’s the story……

Nothing is impossible.

Science is always changing. Miracles are being made everyday & you just never know when YOUR miracle will arrive! 

Xo
Emilee

I can’t wait to see what the next 5 years look like for them. I am so grateful to be alive today, because honestly I never thought I’d see Hayden graduate high-school and he’s 20 years old now. My twins, Macie & Griffin and 17 and applying for colleges this year. It’s just crazy WE made it this far. 

I am so proud of you guys and proud to be your mom ( even if I’m a little annoying at times😂) it’s just because I love you so much ❤️❤️❤️❤️❤️❤️❤️❤️❤️❤️

My journey of #selfimprovement started in 2013! I’ll never forget the day I sat in my first women’s circle at a retreat for women who were lost and at a crossroads.

That woman was me😭

My future looked hopeless.  I lost myself and I lost the vision of all my dreams. 

I don’t know who is out there listening today, but please hear you🎤your future free self is waiting for you!!!!! I understand it may be hard to create a vision 1 year from now, or 5 years from now. You may feel stuck in the mud and unable to make any movement. This is a problem because staying stuck will not move you in the direction you say you want to go. 

The question I was asked in this circle was to share TWO words with the group and the leader would write them on the whiteboard in front of the other woman. I was so scared, literally my body was shaking. I was crying and I was afraid to ask for what I wanted and needed. It never crossed my mind that I was allowed to do that🤷‍♀️

So, I spoke very quietly. 
I said, “respect and love”. 
Rokelle the leader said, “I can’t hear you. Say it louder”. I said it again… respect and love.

Little did I know at the time, my journey of #personalgrowth would lead me on a path to #selflove #selfcompassion and #selfrespect❤️

I never saw that coming in my vision.

I only knew what I felt. I didn’t know the solution to my problems. I do today and I am here to pay it forward to help you. 

One of my dreams for my future in the next year is leading my first healing women’s retreat. This time, I will have graduated from the inner circle to the leader. I can’t believe I’m here. It feels amazing to stand in my power with confidence. 

I want this for you more than you know. The thing is, YOU have to want it for yourself. 

Do you want it? 

The journey starts right now by asking and sharing with me here the same question I was asked.

What do you want more of in your life. Please answer with TWO words. 

If you catch yourself in the story that you can’t have it 🛑 This is an exercise for your mind to CREATE a new vision for yourself. It totally is possible!!!!! I’m living proof and I’m going to help you get there❤️❤️❤️❤️❤️❤️❤️❤️❤️❤️

I know this photo has nothing to do with this message that I am about to share, but hopefully it will make you curious to want to read more. 

I was at a wedding last night, and we were sat at a table with people we didn’t know. Straight across me was a quiet man. My husband recognized him from growing up once he took his sunglasses off. I can’t explain the full story here in detail other than it was one of those serendipity moments where you were placed together at the right place at the right time kind of thing. 

The old me would have not striked up conversation. The new me wanted to know more about this person after he handed me his business card telling us about his nonprofit work. My heart was captured.

Every person has a story, and his story broke my heart and all the other story’s that he was sharing with me. He was diagnosed with stage 4 #coloncancer after his son 18 year old son was diagnosed with cancer. He lost his son to #cancer. I expressed how sorry I was and told him my #childhoodcancer story and it’s as if we are instantly connected. We are both in each others stories.

My heart 💔breaks even more when he tells me his other son died by #suicide on a drug overdose. I could feel his pain, but in a different way. I can’t say I know what it feels like to lose a child, so I just listened and witnessed his pain, it’s something I learned to do as a #griefeducator with #davidkessler🙏

Once I told him I lost my dad to suicide his eyes opened up and there we were, connected through #story. It may seem like a sad story, but in the end like he said, “there are gifts”.

Today he is SAVING lives of first responders through his nonprofit AT EASE, 911aei.org

The things he is making happen to inspire other first responders who want to take their life by suicide is in my mind, one of the hardest things, but one of the most important services needed. He was explaining to me the PTSD that first responders live with and most people don’t know. They hold it in and don’t talk about it. 

Anyway, my message today is if you are or know anyone who is a first responder feeling thoughts of suicide, there is help for you from trained professionals. You Matter❤️

I want to thank & honor my beautiful friend @elly.mayday, who was the BIGGEST advocate for ovarian cancer. She was my first friend on IG and helped me feel less alone. We finally got to meet when she came to visit me. I’ll never forget that visit. We went to dinner, and she could not eat because she got another bowel obstruction. It’s VERY common with ovarian cancer. Ovarian cancer affects a lot more than your ovaries!! Just a few months later, I LOST my friend! I have never cried so hard because it brought reality to my life. What if I am next? I had so many fears of dying.

My entire life, I’ve fought this fear. I was born with cancer. Crazy right? As a little embryo in my mom’s womb, cancer of my connective tissue started to form, and by the time I was 3 years old, that tumor was the size of a grapefruit, taking over my little abdomen. I truly believe that there needs to be more research on #childhoodcancer!! I read 43 children in the U.S. are diagnosed with cancer every day. Worldwide, about 400,000 children and adolescents develop cancer each year, only half of whom are diagnosed. More than 95% of childhood cancer survivors will have significant chronic health issues or a secondary cancer diagnosis like me🥲

I’ve read that ONLY 4% of all federal funding for cancer research is spent on projects involving children’s cancer🤷‍♀️

I share my story to make others aware of the long-term side effects of cancer! I am grateful to be a partner with @larocheposayusa and their cancer squad because they understand cancer care for those of us who have had radiation, #chemotherapy and painful scars from surgery. There are people out there who care and who are making a difference. Until you’ve had cancer, have been touched by cancer or lost a child to cancer, you may not understand the significance of researching for better treatment options and screening tests. Both of my cancers are underfunded, meaning little research goes into them AND I do not have a genetic marker. Where is the research for that? As a cancer survivor, you have so many questions. WHY Me? 

This is MY why. So I can share my story and be a voice to those who can’t❤️Emilee

8 years ago I was diagnosed with advanced stage 3C #ovariancancer. I just celebrated my 39th birthday.

Never in a million years would I had ever imagined I would go through this kind of cancer. To be honest, I thought this was a cancer for women in their late 60’s & 70’s. I was wrong😭

I have always struggled to find my purpose in life. Questioning who am I? Why am I here? What will be the legacy that I leave behind. Before my second cancer diagnosis, no answers came up. I felt worthless & felt like a nobody.

It’s crazy how a cancer diagnosis wake me you the f@$k up and teach you to start living, even when you think you are dying.

The one thing I wanted to do was write a book before I died. I was in a rush, given the stage of cancer I had. I didn’t know how to write. I was a #pilatesteacher and #yogateacher. It didn’t matter because I knew that I had to write a survival guide for the next woman that gets diagnosed and has to go through this debulking surgery and #chemotherapy.

I had a vision that one day my little survival guide would end up in the arms of women from all around the world. Yesterday, this amazing picture was sent to me in my DM. Melissa told me what an inspiration I was to her and that she was about to get ready for her surgery and started to read my book. It’s stories like this that remind me that I do have a purpose and that I am making a difference.

To the woman reading this post who struggles and who is in a crisis and maybe doubting yourself and your purpose like I did, read this amazing poem written by Melissa @melissa.anderson.writes❤️ it took my breath away. She inspires me now to be a better writer.

We are all here to inspire each other, guide each other, help each other and love each other through hard times❤️ Your story will be somebody else’s survival guide one day. Never doubt your vision, follow your heart and everything else will fall into place.

Thank you Melissa for sending me this photo❤️ it means everything to me🙏
P.S. Melissa is holding my first book I wrote. A survival guide for women going through ovarian cancer. Reclaim Your Strength & Hope: by Emilee Garfield

Never underestimate the power of the human body to heal & THRIVE🔥

8 years ago my body felt broken.

I lived with an #ileostomy, which I was able to get reversed.

I was diagnosed with an incurable cancer, and I kicked cancers ass🔥again for the second time in my life.

I’m moving in into a new chapter of my life.

I am stronger than I’ve ever been, literally lifting heavy weights which I thought I’d never do again.

Sure, I still have issues, like a broken bladder ( for real) but I choose not to focus on what’s broken and what doesn’t work anymore.

I choose to focus on what I can do and today I am planking on my reformer which is a lot harder than it looks. Takes a lot of core control.

Movement is my medicine in many ways, for both my physical body and emotional body!

I hope this post inspires you to keep going and never give up.

I teach 7 days a week if you are in need of help reclaiming your strength message me.

Love you,
Emilee

My client did something he thought he would never be able to do again🤗

He tried #pilates with me 💃💃

Most of you know me as a #cancercoach #or a #cancersurvivor, but before I was diagnosed with stage 3c #ovariancancer I was and still am a #pilatesteacher.

MOVEMENT IS MEDICINE🙌🏻🙌🏻🙌🏻🙌🏻

The great thing was that I was honest and said I’d do my best and let’s see what happens.

This leg can lock in place with a Bluetooth device. It can bend and extend and I was able to help my client feel is BOOTY for the first time in 4 months he told me.

My husband is known as The Walking Dr in town and I’ve learned amazing things from him. I love how WE are able to share clients and work as a team. It’s all about teamwork and who can best help our clients.

My client wants to be anonymous, but did say I could post this video to inspire anyone out there who is going through a hard time right now.

Vulnerable post❤️

To be honest, my sons #cancerdiagnosis was a shock to me. It also triggered PTSD in my body. It brought me back to some painful and sad memories. What I’ve learned being trained as a #griefeducator is that #grief comes at different times for people. There is no one way to grieve. 

The #1 form of grief I know I have personally experienced and so have my kids is called #anticipatorygrief. 

What is anticipatory grief? Grief is often understood to happen after a loss occurs, for example after a loved one dies. People expecting a loss may also experience anticipatory grief. This means experiencing the emotions associated with grief before the expected loss actually happens.

This photo of Hayden’s body of emotions makes me cry. To see a child watch their mom almost die and to know they felt guilt around it breaks my 💔But look at what this experience has done for us both. It has bonded us in a way I can’t describe. 

Hayden is able to express his emotions at the age of 20 years old in ways I only wished I could have. This experience has changed him and I already feel it and see it.

We are taught at a young age to “be strong”, “don’t cry”, “get over it” and “don’t be sad”. I just want to remind you today that it’s OK to be sad. It’s OK to feel your feelings! You are not alone in what you feel and it’s good to talk about them.

I grew up ashamed of how I felt and if I only had someone who allowed me to feel my feelings and not judge them I know I would have suffered less emotionally. 

Hayden may not even realize it, but he’s been in training for this. His past experience has helped him through this I believe. 

These are the 5 stages to grief: 
denial, anger, bargaining, depression, and acceptance🙏

Whatever you are feeling is normal❤️

Scroll to the picture blown up and you can see when Hayden was 12, his poor little heart felt GUILT. I never want my kids to ever feel any guilt for what has happened to them or me in their life. I just want them to know how much I love them❤️

I share this post because for 40 years I was sad over the death of my dad when I was 5 and my own cancer diagnosis at age 4. Nobody told me it was called grief.

I can’t thank you enough for all of the messages, phone calls love and support for my boy Hayden.

He is back home in Santa Barbara. He said the hospital was not good for his mindset and the doctor released him early 😂( it was pretty dark and depressing in there).

Hayden had to make some BRAVE decisions. Dr first offered a less extensive surgery keeping the back part of his tibia, but that comes with risks. Higher chance cancer comes back. SO he said, “ Hayden, we can GO BIG  and cut more and give you less anxiety about the cancer coming back”. 

Hayden decided to GO BIG which means a longer recovery. What I didn’t know before surgery was that it isn’t a slam dunk surgery. It will take 4 months of Hayden spending time in his wheelchair and crutches with NO weight at all on his leg before the next scan will determine if the cadaver bone ( dead bone) mates with Hayden’s live bone. Only then, will he begin to slowly start weight bearing and rehab.

If.. the surgery doesn’t take, Dr said the next surgery is BIG a surgery where they would remove bone from his right leg along with blood vessels to transport to his left leg.

It’s just so uncertain right now. 

It’s a wait and see but it is 60% chance it will take and the fact that he’s young helps.

His surgeon came in and told Hayden he is the talk of the town down at UCLA. His tumor is so rare. His bone cancer is so rare and the surgeon said it’s not acting like an Adamantinoma so he felt better going BIG on Hayden’s surgery. 

I know Hayden is going to have a LONG recovery ahead of him, but all of your messages and donations that 100% go to Hayden is seriously what’s keeping him going. 

He loves his work and travels as a pro surf photographer. Dr orders, no work, no travel. Rest, rest, rest and no stress which fuels cancer. So Hayden may be out of work easily for a year. I feel so bad for him so I’m trying my best to help him by spreading his go fund me account.
